## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you're **verifying legacy signatures** (not creating new ones), you have two options:

**Option A — Guard by platform and only verify on Windows/Linux:**
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option B — Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term):**
```csharp
// Re-sign with ECDSA, then verify with ECDSA everywhere
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

Option B requires a one-time re-signing step for all legacy artifacts, but eliminates the legacy algorithm entirely. If you must continue verifying old DSA signatures, restrict that code path to Windows/Linux with a runtime platform check.
